<h3>1. Gong — Deal Intelligence</h3>
<div class="guide-tool-card">
  <div class="guide-tool-header">
    <div>
      <div class="guide-tool-rank">Most impactful for AEs</div>
      <h3 class="guide-tool-name">Gong</h3>
      <p class="guide-tool-tagline">Conversation intelligence that tells you what's actually happening in your deals</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="guide-tool-body">
    <p>Gong is the highest-ROI tool for AEs who manage complex, multi-call deals. It records and analyzes every call, then surfaces the signals that predict whether a deal will close: are you multi-threaded enough? Is the champion engaged? Has the economic buyer gone dark? Is a competitor being evaluated?</p>
    <p>The most valuable Gong feature for AEs is not the call recording — it's the deal intelligence. Gong's AI analyzes conversation patterns across thousands of deals and tells you, in real time, which of your deals are at risk and why. AEs who actively use Gong's deal insights typically improve their forecast accuracy by 20–30% within the first quarter.</p>
    <h4>What AEs actually use it for:</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Reviewing their own calls to identify what they missed or could have handled better</li>
      <li>Sharing call clips with champions to help them sell internally</li>
      <li>Monitoring deal health signals — engagement drop-off, competitor mentions, budget objections</li>
      <li>Preparing for follow-up calls by reviewing what was promised and what questions were left open</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Honest limitations for AEs:</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Value is proportional to call volume — AEs with fewer, longer deals get less signal than those with high call volume</li>
      <li>Requires manager buy-in to unlock coaching features — individual AEs can't self-serve the full value</li>
      <li>Pricing is enterprise-only — typically requires a team license, not individual purchase</li>
