      <p class="guide-tool-tagline">Contact database and sequencing for AEs doing their own expansion prospecting</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="guide-tool-body">
    <p>Apollo is most useful for AEs at companies where SDRs don't handle expansion prospecting — common in SMB and mid-market where AEs own the full cycle including upsell and cross-sell. In these contexts, Apollo gives AEs the contact data and basic sequencing they need to identify and reach new stakeholders at existing accounts without requiring a full SDR workflow.</p>
    <p>The value is straightforward: Apollo's contact database is accurate enough for most US-based prospecting, the free tier is genuinely useful for light usage, and the built-in sequences are sufficient for the volume of outreach most AEs need to do. It's not the right tool for high-volume SDR prospecting, but for an AE sending 20–50 expansion emails per week, it's more than adequate.</p>
    <h4>What AEs actually use it for:</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Finding contact information for new stakeholders at existing accounts</li>
      <li>Light expansion sequencing — reaching out to new contacts at accounts already in the pipeline</li>
      <li>Intent data — Apollo's basic intent signals can surface accounts showing buying behavior</li>
      <li>Company research — Apollo's company profiles provide useful context before calls</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Honest limitations for AEs:</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Data accuracy drops in EMEA and APAC — less useful for AEs with international territories</li>
      <li>If your company already has ZoomInfo or Clay, Apollo may be redundant</li>
      <li>Sequences are functional but not as sophisticated as Outreach or Salesloft</li>
